        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 8:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). (For the habit of kings to lean on the hand of an attendant, see above, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 5:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Answered the man of God, and said, Behold, if the Lord would make windows in heaven, might this thing be?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The king makes no reply; he waits for the result. But the officer on whose arm he leans is not so reticent. Utterly incredulous, he expresses his incredulity in a scoffing way: \"Could this possibly be, even if God were to 'make windows in heaven,' as he did at the time of the Flood (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 7:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and pour through them, instead of rain, as then, a continual shower of fine meal and corn?\" Disbelief is expressed, not only in the prophetic veracity of Elisha, but in the power of God. Hence Elisha's stern reply. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And he said, Behold, thou shalt see it with thine eyes, but shalt not eat thereof.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " At once a threat and a warning. If the thing was to be, and the lord to see it and yet not profit by it, the only reasonable conclusion was that his death was imminent. He was thus warned, and given time to \"set his house in order,\" and to repent and make his peace with the Almighty. Whether he took advantage of the warning, or even understood it, we are not told. 2 Kings 7:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Elisha announced to him the word of the Lord: \"At the (this) time to-morrow a seah of wheaten flour (סלת, see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 5:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") will be worth a shekel, and two seahs of barley a shekel in the gate, i.e., in the market, at Samaria.\" A seah, or a third of an ephah  equals  a Dresden peck (Metze), for a shekel was still a high price; but in comparison with the prices given in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 6:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as those obtained for the most worthless kinds of food, it was incredibly cheap. The king's aide-de-camp (שׁלישׁ: see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 23:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; נשׁען למּלך אשׁר, an error in writing for נשׁ המּלך אשׁר, cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 7:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and for the explanation ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 5:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") therefore replied with mockery at this prophecy: \"Behold (i.e., granted that) the Lord made windows in heaven, will this indeed be?\" i.e., such cheapness take place. (For the construction, see Ewald, 357, b.) The ridicule lay more especially in the \"windows in heaven,\" in which there is an allusion to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 7:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", sc. to rain down a flood of flour and corn. Elisha answered seriously: \"Behold, thou wilt see it with thine eyes, but not eat thereof\" (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 7:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".). The fulfilment of these words of Elisha was brought about by the event narrated in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 7:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
